      clinicalNotes: `Clinical Pearls for Expert Field Assessment:
1. Shock index >1.0 predicts need for massive transfusion better than individual vital signs
2. Mental status is the most sensitive perfusion indicator in young patients
3. Midline cervical tenderness has >95% sensitivity for significant injury - use for clearance
4. Peritoneal signs develop over hours - early abdominal exam may be falsely reassuring
5. Unilateral pupil dilation with declining GCS is herniation until proven otherwise
6. Neurogenic shock produces bradycardia; hemorrhagic shock produces tachycardia
7. Clinical decision rules developed with imaging can guide wilderness clearance
8. Document uncertainty explicitly - "concerning for X, cannot exclude Y"
9. Serial assessment trajectory predicts outcome better than single evaluation
10. Telemedicine can extend expert assessment to remote settings`,
